0occurs%2016%20times%20a%20day%20and%20the%20astronauts%20experience16%20sunrises%20and%20sunsets%20during%20their%20orbit.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20space%20station%20is%20a%20result%20of%20international%20partnership%20among%20five%20space%20agencies%20from%2015%20countries%20that%20joined%20hands%20to%20operates%20it.%20According%20to%20NASA%2C%20the%20space%20station%20has%20been%20continuously%20occupied%20since%20November%202000.%20Usually%2C%20seven%20crew%20live%20and%20work%20on%20the%20space%20station%20which%20is%20bigger%20than%20a%20six-bedroom%20house%2C%20but%20there%20may%20be%20more%20on%20board%20when%20a%20crew%20handover%20takes%20place.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%202017%2C%20US%20astronaut%20Peggy%20Whitson%20set%20the%20record%20of%20spending%20the%20most%20total%20time%20on%20the%20station%20--%20665%20days%20or%20nearly%20two%20years.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20repeated%20day%20to%20night%20shift%20may%20seem%20unnatural%20to%20us%20on%20Earth%20but%20the%20unique%20phenomenon%20is%20a%20boon%20for%20astronauts%20who%20can%20conduct%20diverse%20microbiology%20and%20metallurgy%20experiments%20using%20the%20constant%20shifts%20between%20day%20and%20night.%20Although%20bizarre%2C%20this%20offers%20insights%20that%20would%20not%20be%20possible%20to%20replicate%20on%20Earth.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAccording%20to%20NASA%2C%20after%20leaving%20Earth%2C%20a%20spacecraft%20can%20reach%20the%20space%20station%20in%20as%20quickly%20as%20four%20hours.%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1704089220000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fc.ndtvimg.com%2F2024-01%2Fq30eh3p_astronaut-space-generic-astronaut-generic_625x300_01_January_24.jpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ndtv.com%2Fscience%2Fin-space-new-years-day-is-celebrated-16-times-heres-why-4779431%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22As%20the%20world%20ushered%20in%20the%20new%20year%20on%20Monday%2C%20astronauts%20in%20space%20welcome%202024%20in%20their%20own%20unique%20way%20--%20by%20observing%2016%20New%